The [[upper case]] form of the second [[letter]] of the modern [[w:Greek alphabet|Greek alphabet]], the [[lower case]] form is '''β'''; this letter is named [[beta]] or in [[Greek]] [[βήτα]].

Β is preceded by '''Α α''' and followed by '''Γ γ'''. In modern Greek it represents the [[w:Voiced labiodental fricative|voiced labiodental fricative]] sound of '''v''' found in the English words ''have'' and ''vase''.

The shape of the letter is derived from the Phoenician letter [[Beth (letter)|Beth]] [[Image:phoenician_beth.png|20px|Beth]].

